Message.Title: Getting close to crucial levels
Message.Msg: Google has remained weak over the past few weeks. It has corrected by more than 6% from the highs, but there has not been any major sign on revival. But it seems that the possibility of a rebound is getting higher, and the stock may attempt a bounce soon after touching $855. Meanwhile, the Attorney General of Connecticut raised concerns about privacy issues related to Glass. The Attorney General wants to know how Google will disclose the privacy risks associated with the product or obtain consent for collection of data. This is understandable as most new technologies are viewed with skepticism initially. However, there may be many relevant concerns amongst people, especially those who will not use the product. They would like to know how the facial recognition capabilities will affect their privacy. These, and more concerns will emerge and the technology will ultimately need to get acceptance from various sections of the society. The product is likely to be a niche product and hence the non-users will like to have their say. Google does not want to get into legal troubles related to the launch and it may need to take a more open approach towards addressing the privacy concerns. It is already facing lawsuits about dominance, privacy issues, patent infringement etc. in various courts around the world. Though the patent lawsuits are not going to be game changing for Google, one can not ignore the fact that the size and the magnitude is growing all the time. Even small companies like MGT Capital Investments (MGT) are filing multi-billion dollar lawsuits against bigger companies. Furthermore, Google will now have to increasingly deal with the burden of expectations over its future launches. This is because the stock has already performed, while the fundamentals may have a little catching up to do. The recent correction has reduced the flab and froth, but still the market may not take negative surprises too kindly.
